The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | CHIT CHAT
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      CHIT CHAT
                                          
	Kid canvas        
	More than 1,000 kids explored their creativity at an art fair for children organised by Apeejay Anand Childrens Library on February 26. The chief guest was Sanjay Wadvani, the British deputy high commissioner.         
	With the theme Hazaron Khwahishein, it saw students from schools like Birla High School for Boys, Akshar, Mahadevi Birla Girls Higher Secondary School and NGOs like Cini Asha, All Bengal Womens Union and Mentaid, painting on T-shirts.         
	Aurajit Sadhukhan from Park Institution, Akshay Ginodia of Sree Jain Vidyalaya and Manoj Bopari from SOS Village came first, second and third, respectively.         
	Girl child focus                
	Ballygunge Shiksha Sadan celebrated its 60th year on February 26 with a performance by NGO Khelaghar, a medley of songs and folk dances by students.        
	Theatre personality and alumnus of the school Dolly Basu, along with police commissioner Gautam Mohan Chakrabarti and Sheriff of Calcutta Utpal Chatterjee were the guests of honour.        
	Said Principal Sunita Sen: Our themes for the 60th year celebrations are empowerment of the girl child, peace and the environment. The school has a series of programmes lined up for the year.                                                                                                                                                          
